segments.text: And this is the story of your life and your family.
First, where were you born and in which part?
En 1906, el día 3 de... El día 3 de mayo.
Pues dígame sobre su mamá y papá.
He came with me to the United States.
My father told my mother that he died in Mexico.
When I was four years old, I barely remember.
In what year did he die?
But before his mother came to the United States.
How many children are in your family?
I ask about your mother and father's family first.
That's what you want to ask.
Well, there are two sisters, women, and we are four men in the family.
And your family lived in Mexico, in general?
And what town is near General Treviño, the biggest town?
I don't remember very well, but I think it's Mierta Maulipas, I think.
And what kind of work did your father have?
My mother said, many years ago, those people who lived...
I think my father, his father...
I think they were like little children, my grandfather.
They traveled from one town to another.
in burros with, I don't know, with merchandise that they were going to sell here to other towns.
And in this general Trabiño, another town?
No, it was when they were living, because my mother is from the state of San Luis Potosí.
But I don't know where his father lived.
It would be more to the other side of Monterrey.
And he was in the merchandise.
And your father, what kind of work did he have?
Yes, to make the walls of the house.
My mother used to tell me that when they moved to nearby beds to raise three children, he worked in a ranch.
Planting, the work of the boss, I think.
It was a ranch of another person.
And after her father died, what did her mother do?
Well, she worked to support us, the youngest ones who were at home.
Well, in the kitchen, with other people.
And this was in general travel?
Yes, but here we grew up a little bit.
And then we came to the United States.
I was about 15 years old when I came here.
And for what reason did your family come to the United States?
To work, because you know very well that in Mexico it is very hard to earn a living for food.
Because she was the only mother, you see?
She had to work to keep us.
Yo vine la primera vez que no he vuelto a ir para atrás con el hermano mayor.
¿En qué clase de, pues, en qué modo venían a los Estados Unidos?
Before that, there was a train here from Robes Town to Pérguit del Valle.
Well, when did you leave Mexico?
Did you go through the border?
That's where we crossed over to this side?
From Rome, we came here to a town where the train arrived, to Sanfordais, Texas.
I don't remember very well, but he was retired from Rome.
And that's where the train was coming from.
I don't know where it was coming from, but it was coming from here.
From there we came to Driscoll, a town about 20 miles away.
And from there we went to Petronila, a ranch close by.
I don't remember exactly, but it was about 10 miles away, I think.
That's where we got to that ranch.
And does everyone work in your family?
When there was cotton, we would play.
Yes, I was about 15 years old when we came here to Petronilla.
And in Mexico, are there problems with the war in these days?
I heard that there was war, fighting with each other, the same brothers, the same children from Mexico.
And war is not the reason for your family?
There are no problems for your family with war?
I can't understand if there are problems between families.
Because among the families we were four men and two women.
In these days in Mexico, what kind of things do you remember about your home?
What kind of house did your family have there?
Well, it was a very poor house.
Yes, she was the only one who worked there.
And the town was very big or small?
No, it was a small town.
They say that now it's very big.
Well, if I had a chance one day, I could go, but who knows?
Is life very different here in Mexico?
Some people who come from there tell me that it's very hard to work there.
They pay a lot of money a day.
But they almost tell me that with the 30 pesos they earn in one day, they don't have anything to eat.
They tell me that everything is very expensive.
to eat and all that, clothes and everything.
Once I was told by a man who was working here that a pair of shoes... Who's like these?
You can't buy shoes for every boy or girl.
You can buy them, but I'm sure that in a week they won't have food for the family.
It's easier to live here, it's lighter.
For a family that has three or four families, it's much lighter here.
And this is the reason why you don't want to live in Mexico or other places?
Well, I would like to just go for a walk, not to live.
I've spent most of my life here.
And if I leave now, since I'm old, where am I going to work?
I don't know how to work there.
And here, well, the time I've been working here with this lady, with all the families of God,
I can do any construction work.
Not very well, but I understand the work.
And you also had a family.
In what year did you get married?
And where was your wife from?
When I saw her for the first time, I lived here for about a year, a year and a half, around 1944.
When I met her for the first time,
In what way is it possible to meet her?
I don't remember how old I was.
But more or less, I was about... 19 or 20 years old.
We met for the first time in the dance.
I came to the dance too, and so did I.
We got married in a short time.
And most of them are called?
And Concepcion Sanchez is the second.
And Antonio Sanchez is the youngest.
The three of them are married?
The eldest one lives here in Petronilla.
And the second one lives in Por la Vaca.
And Antonio lives here in Corpus.
And what kind of work does your son have?
And he has a school and everything.
It took him a year to finish the whole big school here in Robstown.
But since he was very young, he started working at a gas station here.
When I left school, I came and worked until about 10 or 11 at night.
Helping there, selling gasoline and other tires that accompanied.
And after that, he liked that job and he needed a year to finish school.
And then, he was sent to the service, to the army.
There, he finished the school that the government gave him.
And he studied mechanics there too.
And when he came, he continued to work in the same garage.
And soon after, the boss couldn't work there anymore because he owed a lot.
And then he passed it on to him in the middle.
so that Antonio could make payments for what he owed to the paper company and other things, to other iron companies that he bought to make the car.
Well, Antonio gathered all the money and made a payment there, another payment to another company, until he paid everything that the boss owed him.
Then he bought everything from the boss.
Everything he had inside the farm.
And the husbands of your daughters, what kind of work do they have?
Antonio's wife... ...was working for about a year, recently, in a clothing store.
I don't know why she's studying there.
She goes there in the morning.
I think it's like 2 in the afternoon.
I don't know why she's studying.
Maybe she's going to get a job in a store or something else.
Do you think that studies are a good thing?
Well, because if you know more, one day you can get a job where you can earn more money.
Because right now, a boy who doesn't finish school, goes to a company to look for a job.
The first thing they ask him, the boss there tells him, do you have your diploma?
That's the first thing they ask him.
She doesn't ask him if he wants to work.
She asks him, do you have your diploma?
So I think the man can say, well, there is work.
For this reason, it is necessary to study.
And the husband of your other daughter, what kind of work?
What kind of work did he have?
When the children leave the school, he cleans them.
The inside, the floor, the walls, the floors, and all that.
And is he from Texas, or from which part?
He's from here in the United States.
Is he the husband of your other daughter?
He's worked there almost all his life because his father is a mayor of that ranch.
I have known the father of my son-in-law who lives in Petronila since 1918.
I knew the mother of my son-in-law, also a lady.
Well, I got married, your family, he got married, your family, my nephew.
And then, from here in Petronila, he came to a ranch here at the airport.
It was a very big ranch there.
He was also in Mayoloma with that same boss.
And this boy, the husband of my girlfriend, she was already old and they came here to school.
My girlfriend was also at school.
With families who are together and get married.
We've known each other for many years.
Is his father from Mexico or from here?
No, he's from the United States.
For the rest of his life?
He's the mayor of that ranch.
He's been the mayor for many years.
Yes, because I was there in 1918.
In 1919, with the churrasco here in Corpus.
I don't know if you remember, but have you read in the books?
I think it was the first one, I think.
Well, it's a lot of air, very strong.
But it was different from a hurricane.
It's a kind of, how do you say storm?
In about a month or two months, I came here with my family.
My eldest father, from the whole family.
From this family here in this ranch?
He lived there in that big house.
So I'm here with them, in the same family, working here.
Was this your first job here in the United States?
I was a kid here in Petronila, picking cotton.
And when I came here to work with the uncle, we called him uncle.
All the people call him uncle, uncle.
Well, where we are right now, there were no houses here, nothing.
There was a shed where they had a lot of cows and mules, horses, to work the land, because in those years they worked with pure beasts, horses, the land.
Here in this place where we are, it was a pure mountain.
And here, Juan Deíce gave the first job, taking out...
taking out the mountain with a sledgehammer.
I was looking at my hands with some water balls here.
I was working like this, taking out the trees.
But I was very young, I was about 15, like 15 and a half years old.
And in the afternoon I was looking at my hands here with some water balls.
It was the first job I did here.
Here in this little piece, we are talking right now.
And there are many trees here these days.
And small, big mosques and all that.
This is the Hawaii that goes here in 44.
It was pure land, just raised like that.
Back then there were a lot of guayines, bogues, carts.
There weren't many at that time.
Well, after the elimination of the mountain and the fields, what kind of crops?
This seed that they plant now, they didn't plant it to sell it like they sell it now.
They only used it for mules and horses.
There were no factories where they bought that seed.
And were there many families that lived here on this ranch?
I think there were about ten families.
All that land that you see on the other side of the house, the old man's house, there are only houses for the people who lived here, who worked here, in the works here.
Yes, on the other side of the road.
On the other side of the road.
And these houses were made of wood?
Yes, with light and things like this?
No, ma'am, at that time there was no light.
And how many fours did you have in these houses?
Well, there were some that had a little room.
There was another one that had two.
A small table like this, just standing.
The door, to go to the other room, everything.
The floor, just a table like this.
I don't remember, but when I came here, those houses were already made.
When I was 10 years old, I lived here.
He was going to build another house.
I think they came from Corpo.
They came here to make houses for the people.
A big house to put corn and seeds for the horses.
But now there are no houses?
People started moving from one place to another.
And then they took all the land to plant his son-in-law.
Then the brothers were distributed from all over the land.
From all over the land, yes.
Each son got a little piece.
How many sons were in this uncle's family?
The uncles are... Let me see if I remember.
I think there are three men.
And for this reason, after the uncle died, each one of the children had a smaller part.
I think it's almost the same.
And Mexico is also the custom?
In your years here, do you think about life in Mexico and here to make comparisons?
The life in Mexico and here?
Well, for me... For someone who has family, life is much better here.
Well, I'm going to tell you why.
Because here there is more work.
And you can find... ...merchandise or food, whatever it is... ...a little cheaper than in Mexico.
Although right now everything is a little expensive here.
The war in Mexico, the revolution.
Do you know any stories about this?
About the men who were in the revolution or what?
There comes Pancho Villa, Obregon, I don't remember.
And this is a thing from your experience, but it's a very old thing.
Well, some people say that the revolution was a good thing for Mexico, and others say that it was a bad thing.
What do you think about this?
Well, because I've heard of talks, now that I'm older, that there were some who were in the revolution,
fighting for the good of Mexico, for all the people.
They weren't fighting like others, like the others, because it was the government that was fighting and others who stood up against the government to fight.
And there were some who talk now that they were fighting so that the poor people had something to eat.
Because of how poor there are many people.
Well, in Mexico, before the revolution, there were many schools.
For example, do you study in Mexico?
Yes, because my mom came here and we have to work to maintain the trip.
I like how she maintained us when we were little.
How many years did you study?
A little, but a little is a year or two years in school?
I'm going to tell you the truth.
I haven't learned English here with these people.
They speak Spanish to me all the time.
I didn't learn to speak well with them.
I understand what they say and all that.
And it wasn't necessary to learn English.
Well, yes, but it's very hard for me to speak English.
Because if I say something that is not right, there it is.
It's very different to talk to a lady than to talk to a gentleman.
Well, because you can say something bad when you're talking to a lady who doesn't know English perfectly.
But you speak a little bit of English.
Well, a little bit of one thing, a little bit of another.
Well, this old man doesn't speak English, he speaks Spanish.
But I understand everything he tells me.
He brings me things from there, he tells me in English, and I take it with me.
This old man who works here with you, he doesn't speak Spanish?
He speaks Spanish, but as I tell him.
There are times that he says something to me in Spanish that is not true.
But he is talking to me.
If I start speaking English with you, I can say something bad to you.
That's why it's very hard to talk to a woman.
With a good man, it's much more different.
Yes, because if you say something bad, they don't pay much attention.
Well, yes, maybe it's easier for men to talk to men and women.
Antonio is the one who speaks the most correct English.
Because he studied it a lot.
And your daughters went to school, right?
Yes, they went to school, but they don't speak the correct English like Antonio.
You look at Antonio speaking English, and you say, well, he's an American who speaks English.
Because he finished the whole school when he came from the service, from the army.
He went to the school here in Del Mar to finish the school.
He went to the school to learn how to put stickers on the cars.
And then he went to school to study mechanics at the distro.
What do you call big engines?
He went to school for mechanics.
And your children never visited Mexico either?
The older girl is the one who goes to Mexico instead.
How long have you been doing this?
I used to smoke... Cigarettes like... Like 30 years.
And now I have like... Like 5 years left.
Yes, I smoke in the house, one or two.
But at work I don't smoke anything.
It doesn't tempt me to see other people who are smoking to make me want to smoke a cigarette.
At night, when I just finished dinner, I turn on the TV, I grab a cigarette.
I'm watching TV all the time.
Y usted vive cerca de aquí?
